node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Italy • Travel • Passion in Manarola. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
▪ One of the tiniest of Italy’s Cinque Terre 🇮🇹, Manarola is a rainbow of brightly colored homes piled one on top of another above the indigo Ligurian Sea. Perched on a large rock and surrounded by steep terraced vineyards, the seaside village looks straight out of an old Italian movie, with postcard-perfect sights at every turn.🤩🪨🌈✨⁣

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Italy • Travel • Passion on August 07, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
▪ Atrani is a coastal fishing village with a population of less than one thousand. It nestles in the divide of two steep cliffs on the shore of the Tyrrhenian Sea. Its tier upon tier of multi-colored houses rises above a beautiful stretch of pristine sand. It is one of the most idyllic and picturesque settings in Italy.⁣

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Italy • Travel • Passion in Procida. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
▪ Procida, a tiny spot of land in the Bay of Naples, might be best known as the island between Ischia and Capri. But in late January, it was named Italy's Capital of Culture for 2022, beating nine other candidates—a mix of cities and small towns—and becoming the first island to ever be granted the title.⁣
••••••••••••••••••••••••••••⁣
